occurrences.line_text: Mine onely foe, mine onely deadly dread,
Mine onely foe, mine onely deadly dread,
And fie on Fortune mine auowed foe,
Did seeme to laugh on me, and fauour mine intent.
Was firmest fixt in mine extremest case,
Should haue mine onely daughter to his Dame,
Therefore since mine he is, or free or bond,
Redoubted knight, that for mine onely sake
For mine offence and heedlesse hardiment,
And with reprochfull shame mine honour shent,
My hart, my hands, mine eyes, and all assayd?
Mine auncestry from famous Coradin,
Yet nought can quench mine inly flaming syde,
And his whot fire burnes in mine entrails bright,
Another blis before mine eyes I place,
But giue me leaue to follow mine emprise.
But sith thou hast found fauour in mine eye,
My selfe well wote, and mine vnequall fate;
Against his foe and mine: watch thou I pray;
Presume so high to stretch mine humble quill?
Yet will I not fro mine owne loue remoue,
But mine is not (quoth she) like others wound;
That all mine entrailes flow with poysnous gore,
But wicked fortune mine, though mind be good,
The like that mine, may be your paine another tide.
Take then to you this Dame of mine (quoth hee)
Why doth mine hand from thine auenge abstaine,
Last turne was mine, well proued to my paine,
Yet was he meet, vnlesse mine eye did faine,
Thy ruefull plight I pitty as mine owne.
Whereof when tydings came vnto mine eare,
There did I finde mine onely faithfull frend
Was mine and his ï¿½mylias libertie.
To my friends good, more then for mine owne sake,
Mine eye was fixt, for feare of her offence:
And Mulla mine, whose waues I whilom taught to weep.
He, whether mine seem'd fayrer in his eye,
Fro me reft mine away by lawlesse might,
And left me here, both his & mine owne loue to morne.
So his encreased, but mine did empaire.
Her weary barke at last vppon mine Isle did rest.
I hold mine owne, and so will hold it still.
But want of meanes hath bene mine onely let,
Is mine owne loue, though me she haue forlore,
I should no creature ioyne vnto mine ayde,
Ne would I gladly combate with mine host,
That I disdain'd amongst mine equall peares
Fit mate for such a mincing mineon,
Like as Minerua, being late returnd
And Dart, nigh chockt with sands of tinny mines.
Whilst thus they mingled were in furious armes,
Which mingled all with sweate, did dim his eye.
Mingled emongst loose Ladies and lasciuious boyes.
And scorned parts were mingled with the fine,)
As smoke and sulphure mingled with confused strife.
In fleshly lust were mingled both yfere,
And mingled them with perfect vermily,
And mingled with the raskall rablement,
And them amongst were mingled here and there,
To make one minime of thy poore handmayd,
By chance he certaine miniments forth drew,
The paw yet missed not his minisht might,
Against the viaundes should be ministred.
Ministreth matter fit, which tempred right
Dragons, and Minotaures, and feendes of hell,
There many Minstrales maken melody,
Of Minstrals, making goodly meriment,
Whose smallest minute lost, no riches render may.
Nigh thirtie minutes to the Southerne lake;
Quites Mirabell from dreed:
Fayre Mirabella was her name, whereby
Fayre Mirabellaes punishment
Till Mirabellaes fortunes I doe further say.
Ensample take of Mirabellaes case,
By miracle, not yet appearing playne,
A miracle of natures goodly grace,
As if some miracle of heauenly hew
Miraculous may seeme to him, that reades
So oft as Slowth still in the mire did stand.
And gathering vp himselfe out of the mire,
As he recoyled backward, in the mire
Lying on ground, all soild with bloud and mire:
Through the dull billowes thicke as troubled mire,
Nor sea of licour cold, nor lake of mire,
Ordained hath, he clothes with sinfull mire,
Through mirkesome aire her readie way she makes.
The Mirrhe sweete bleeding in the bitter wound,
And in her hand she held a mirrhour bright,
The God himselfe vewing that mirrhour rare,
In this faire mirrhour maist behold thy face,
So glorious mirrhour of celestiall grace,
To her reuealed in a mirrhour plaine,
Where when she had espyde that mirrhour fayre,
I in my fathers wondrous mirrhour saw,
That mirrhour, wherein the sicke Damosell
Mirrour of grace and Maiestie diuine,
To be a mirrour to all mighty men,
In whose pure minde, as in a mirrour sheene
In mirrours more then one her selfe to see,
She soone left off her mirth and wanton play,
Their wanton sports and childish mirth did play,
Which turned hath great mirth, to mourning sad,
All bent to mirth before the bride was bedded,
Sweete Goddesses all three which me in mirth do cherry.
Planted with mirtle trees and laurels greene,
A gloomy groue of mirtle trees did rise,
For since mine eye your ioyous sight did mis,
And swim in pleasure, which thou here doest mis;
Behaues with cares, cannot so easie mis.
For which ye men do striue: few get, but many mis.
What wonder then, if one of women all did mis?
Certes ye misauised beene, t'vpbrayd
Missing the marke of his misaymed sight
And chyde at him, that made her misbelieue:
And drawing nigh him said, Ah misborne Elfe,
Repined greatly, and did him miscall,
Whom she with leasings lewdly did miscall,
Miscalling me by many a bitter name,
But is miscaried with the other Spheres.
Of her miscarriage should in her be fond,
The meede of thy mischalenge and abet:
That mischieuous mischance his life & limbes did spare.
From foule mischance; ne did it euer rest,
And teares it all with terrible mischance.
And there his mortall part by great mischance
On silly Dame, subiect to hard mischaunce,
But in her way throwes mischiefe and mischaunce,
But to delay the heat, least by mischaunce
And through his mayled hauberque, by mischaunce
Sith late mischaunce had her compeld to chaunge
But walkt each where, for feare of hid mischaunce,
But Artegall beholding his mischaunce,
And heare th'aduenture of her late mischaunce;
Vnto a straunge mischaunce, that menac'd her decay.
The reach of men, through flight into fond mischief fell.
So mischief fel vpon the meaners crowne;
Least suddaine mischiefe ye too rash prouoke:
To worken mischiefe and auenging woe,
She brought to mischiefe through occasion,
I meant to purge both with a third mischiefe,
Falne into mischiefe through intemperaunce,
But in her way throwes mischiefe and mischaunce,
For tombling into mischiefe vnespide.
That none of them foule mischiefe could eschew,
Of secret foes, that him shall make in mischiefe fall.
In mischiefe, was much moued at so pitteous sight.
For feare of mischiefe, which she did forecast
Still when he mused on his late mischiefe,
In th'other was, this Mischiefe, that Mishap;
For so huge mischiefe, and vile villany
A new vnknowen mischiefe did from him remoue.
Misdoubted lost through mischiefe that befell;
Perceiu'd would breede great mischiefe, he bethought
The wicked steele for mischiefe first ordained,
This mischiefe framd, for their first loues defeature,
Then two speares length; So mischiefe ouermatcht the wronger.
By some bad spirit, that it to mischiefe bore,
And mickle mischiefe vnto many a knight,
Vntill late mischiefe did vppon me light,
In mischiefe: for her selfe she onely vext;
How they might make him into mischiefe fall,
He saw, the present mischiefe to redresse,
To cloke the mischiefe, which he inly ment,
The guilt on him, which did this mischiefe breed,
Of all his mischiefe, and late lucklesse smart;
Contented, greater mischiefe on her threw,
Thenceforth more mischiefe and more scath he wrought
Full many mischiefes follow cruell VVrath;
That neuer man such mischiefes did torment;
Of grieuous mischiefes, which a wicked Fay
Infinite mischiefes of them do arize,
That plagues, and mischiefs, and long misery
How many mischieues should ensue his heedlesse hast.
Quoth then the knight, by whose mischieuous arts
And his mischieuous bow full readie bent,
That mischieuous mischance his life & limbes did spare.
To bring to passe his mischieuous intent,
Of his mischieuous deedes, and said, that hee
Through mischieuous debate, and deadly feood,
That seem'd he was full bent to some mischieuous deede.
And for what cause so great mischieuous smart
Through misconceipt; all vnawares espide
And misty dampe of misconceiuing night,
Or to misconstrue of a mans intent,
Which she misconstruing, thereby esteemd
And to him said, Goe now proud Miscreant,
In which amazement, when the Miscreant
Vile Miscreant (said he) whither doest thou flie
False traitour miscreant, thou broken hast
From her, vnto the miscreant him selfe,
And Ymner slew, or Logris miscreate;
Eftsoones he tooke that miscreated faire,
Ne mortall steele emperce his miscreated mould.
Yet if thou wilt renounce thy miscreaunce,
And said, Arise thou cursed Miscreaunt,
The faire Irena with his foule misdeede,
Durst not approch for dread, which she misdeem'd,
His sence abusd, and made him to misdeeme
Such, as no doubt of him he neede misdeeme.
These gentle Ladies will misdeeme too light,
Which carry colours faire, that feeble eies misdeeme.
Couered with darknesse and misdeeming night,
Through light misdeeming of her loialtie,
Misdeeming sure that her those flames did burne;
Your high displesure, through misdeeming bred:
Sith thou misdeem'st so much of things in sight?
As much disdeigning to be so misdempt,
Is not occasiond through my misdesert,
If he misdid, he on himselfe did dight,
Which by misdiet daily greater grew:
Surfeat, misdiet, and vnthriftie wast,
Of so vnmanly maske, in misery misdight.
Can guilen Argus, when she list misdonne?
He fled for feare of that he had misdonne,
Or did misdoubt some ill, whose cause did not appeare.
Misdoubted lost through mischiefe that befell;
She gan to cast in her misdoubtfull mynde
Therefore misdoubting, least he should misguyde
Was almost dead, misdoubting least of new
The Miser threw him selfe, as an Offall,
Now miserable I Fidessa dwell,
As miserable louers vse to rew,
O miserable men, that to him subiect arre.
What now is left of miserable wights,
Redresse the wrong of miserable wight,
There dwels he euer, miserable swaine,
That all the gods did mone her miserable case.
Reioyced at his miserable case,
As now in miserable state he stands;
For wretched woman, miserable wight,
So miserably him all helpelesse slew,
Into this life with woe, and end with miseree.
Till death make one end of my dayes and miserie.
Then waste in woe and wailefull miserie.
And more, I graunt to thy great miserie
Knowing the miserie of their estate,
Vnto her natiue home from mortall miserie.
And sigh full sore, to heare the miserie,
His miserie to be augmented more,
To gather breath in many miseries.
To see sad pageants of mens miseries,
With wretched miseries, and woefull ruth,
And mortall miseries doth make her play.
Vouchsafe to stay your steed for humble misers sake.
He stayd his steed for humble misers sake,
The God of his desire, the ioy of misers blind.
That plagues, and mischiefs, and long misery
Vnto you bring, to ease you of your misery.
Will not long misery late mercy make,
For misery craues rather mercie, then repriefe.
As gentle Ladies helplesse misery.
To cloud my daies in dolefull misery,
He could no more but her great misery bemone.
Your misery, how fell ye in this state.
Of so vnmanly maske, in misery misdight.
That meant to make aduantage of his misery.
That for her sake fell into misery:
Nor better cheare to shew in misery,
Had him misfalne in his aduenturous quest;
Whereto great comfort in her sad misfare
Full of melancholie and sad misfare,
That much did ease his mourning and misfare:
Against all hard mishaps and fortunelesse misfare.
His stubborne heart, that neuer felt misfare
The whole occasion of his late misfare,
Crying aloud to shew her sad misfare
Through daily mourning, and nightly misfare:
For so misfeigning her true knight to bee:
And to vpbrayd that chaunce, which him misfell,
With that misformed spright he backe returnd againe.
Are you in this misformed house to dwell?
And that misformed shape mis-shaped more:
Hath with so huge misfortune you opprest?
Misfortune waites aduantage to entrap
What great misfortune hath betidd this knight?
Seemed some great misfortune to deplore,
Not to prouoke misfortune, nor to weene
The same one day, as me misfortune led,
Should of his dearest daughters hard misfortune heare.
Into misfortune fell, as ye did heare,
What hard misfortune brought me to the same;
And hauing now misfortune got for guide,
Or hard misfortune she was thence conuayd,
Before misfortune did his hew deface:
To tell through what misfortune he had far'd,
That by misfortune in his hand did fall.
In hope ye will not turne misfortune to my blame
What May-game hath misfortune made of you?
And in his fall misfortune him mistooke;
But through misfortune, which did me abase
As he of some misfortune were afrayd:
Of her sad troubles and misfortunes hard:
And heaped with so huge misfortunes, reach?
Does make her selfe misfortunes piteous pray.
She sought with ruth to salue his sad misfortunes sore.
Great ruth through her misfortunes tragicke stowre;
In sad misfortunes foule deformity,
To saue her chylde, which in misfortunes mouth was plaste.
Of thy vaine boast, and spoile of loue misgotten,
Leaue faytor quickely that misgotten weft
Therefore misdoubting, least he should misguyde
What doe I see? what hard mishap is this,
His threatned speare, as if some new mishap
What hard mishap him brought to such distresse,
Vnweeting, and vnware of such mishap,
The warlike ryder to his most mishap;
Some hard mishap, in hazard of his life:
Lamenting his mishap and heauy plight;
In th'other was, this Mischiefe, that Mishap;
Till by mishap he in his foemens hand did light.
His hard mishap in dolor to deplore,
An hard mishap and disauentrous case
But what mishap thus long him fro my selfe remoues?
And brauely mounted to his most mishap:
of Artegals mishap,
Sometime she feared, least some hard mishap
My Lord, your Loue, by hard mishap doth lie
Vnhappy Squire, what hard mishap thee brought
Of former daies mishap, his sorrowes wicked sourse.
For that mishap, yet seeing him to mourne,
Affraid, least to themselues the like mishappen might.
Mishaps are maistred by aduice discrete,
And maister these mishaps with patient might;
Yet death then, would the like mishaps forestall,
It was in my mishaps, as hitherward
Against all hard mishaps and fortunelesse misfare.
My hard mishaps, that ye may learne to shonne;
Of my mishaps, art mou'd to wish me better,
Monstrous mishapt, and all his backe was spect
Thus to mislead me, whiles I you obaid:
That him too light of credence did mislead,
His foolish maladie, and long time had misled.
Of yore, and many had ylike misled:
Whose looser thought will lightly be misled,
How he mis-led the simple peoples traine,
To craue the same, whom errour so misled,
For of the meane he greatly did misleeke.
Mote not mislike you also to abate
And both misplast; that when th'one forward yode,
And greater shame t'abide so great misprize,
With misregard, that some rash witted wight,
Distempred through misrule and passions bace:
As her repenting so to haue missayd,
But brought forth speeches myld, when she would haue missayd.
Though out of course, yet hath not bene mis-sayd,
O graunt that of my loue at last I may not misse.
Of all whose weight, he would not misse a fether.
He should his purpose misse, which close he ment:
he saues, his loue doth misse.
Against him ran; but th'one did misse his marke,
For he, that once hath missed the right way,
The paw yet missed not his minisht might,
I weene, would you misseeme; for ye bene tall,
Forcing to doe, that did him fowle misseeme:
Who with her witchcraft and misseeming sweete,
And this misseeming hew your manly looks doth marre?
For neuer knight I saw in such misseeming plight.
And this misseeming discord meekely lay aside.
Met her in such misseeming foule array;
But misseth bow, and shaftes, and buskins to her knee.
That her mis-shape much helpt; and her foule heare
Art thou misshaped thus, as now I see?
And that misformed shape mis-shaped more:
That her misshaped parts did them appall,
Her neather partes misshapen, monstruous,
A rude, misshapen, monstrous rablement,
Of fowle misshapen wights, of which some were
And horribly misshapes with vgly sightes,
For howsoeuer it may grow mis-shapt,
His mightie armour, missing most at need;
Missing the marke of his misaymed sight
Who missing of the marke which he had eyde,
And missing it, faine from themselues to flie;
Vnlouely Proteus, missing to his mind
That not a dram was missing of their right,
That many there were missing, which were ded,
Then found he many missing of his crew,
A foggy mist, that ouercast the day,
A foggy mist had couered all the land;
But whenas Mammon saw his purpose mist,
But feard to wander in that wastfull mist,
As when a foggy mist hath ouercast
The mist of griefe dissolu'd, did into vengeance powre.
And left sore wounded: but when her he mist,
Like to a Tygre that hath mist his pray,
Now here, now there, and oft him neare he mist;
Both which fraile men do oftentimes mistake,
Whiles cause not well conceiued ye mistake.
The guilty cup she fained to mistake,
For me he did mistake that Squire to be;
As that I did mistake the liuing for the ded.
But Calidore he greatly did mistake;
To weet, what mister wight was so dismayd:
What mister wight (said he) and how arayd?
What mister wight that was, and whence deriued,
What mister wight it was that so did plaine?
What mister wight he was, or what he ment:
Ne weene what mister maladie it is,
What mister wight (quoth he) and how far hence
What mister men, and eke from whence they were.
A sacrament prophane in mistery of wine.
When foggy mistes, or cloudy tempests haue
And shew'd him how through error and mis-thought
Disperst the shadowes of the mistie night,
So liuely and so like, that many it mistooke.
Which they so much mistooke, they tooke delight
Whereas no liuing creature he mistooke,
Which was not hers, as many it mistooke,
And in his fall misfortune him mistooke;
And with corruptfull brybes is to vntruth mis-trayned.
And to his mistresse each himselfe stroue to aduaunce.
As in their mistresse reskew, whom they lad;
To sing his mistresse prayse, and let him mend,
His mistresse prayses, sweetly caroled,
So great a mistresse of her art she was,
In combats of sweet loue, and with his mistresse toyed.
For feare her mistresse shold haue knowledge gayned,
Therefore vnto her mistresse most vnkind
Vnto her mistresse, being halfe dismayd,
As for my name, it mistreth not to tell;
He started vp, as seeming to mistrust,
Ne reckt she, who her meaning did mistrust;
He lookt askew with his mistrustfull eyes,
And misty dampe of misconceiuing night,
Like the faire Morning clad in misty fog did shew.
But forst to trot on foot, and foule misused,
Now scratching her, and her loose locks misusing;
The more they him misust, and cruelly did beat.
His late miswandred wayes now to remeasure right.
By Artegall, misween'd for her owne Knight,
Why then should witlesse man so much misweene
And rash misweening doe thy hart remoue:
Who likewise sought her louer long miswent,
The swelling of his wounds to mitigate,
Ne shall he yet his wrath so mitigate,
To mitigate his stubborne mallady:
Did mitigate the fiercenesse of their mode,
Ne ought mote ease or mitigate his paine,
For naught the same may calme ne mitigate,
So did he mitigate Sir Artegall;
Began to mitigate his swelling sourse,
And like a Persian mitre on her hed
And crowned mitre rudely threw aside;
To Isis, deckt with Mitre on her hed,
And Moone-like Mitre to a Crowne of gold,
They wore rich Mitres shaped like the Moone,
And counsell mittigates the greatest smart;
Mixed with manly sternnesse did appeare
And manly terrour mixed therewithall,
And mixed threats among, and much vnto her vowed.
Mongst ioyes mixing some tears, mongst wele, some wo,
Mixt with a murmuring winde, much like the sowne
Amongst these mighty men were wemen mixt,
Great pleasure mixt with pittifull regard,
The metall first he mixt with MedÃ¦wart,
That euer mixt their song with light licentious toyes.
And all the grauell mixt with golden owre;
A direfull stench of smoke and sulphure mixt
Through goodly mixture of complexions dew;
From aged Mnemon; for my wits bene light.
Old Mnemon. Therefore Sir, I greet you well
A shepheard, when Mnemosyne he catcht:
All which, and thousands mo do make a loathsome life.
In vaine to mocke, or mockt in vaine to bee:
The laughing stocke of fortunes mockeries,
And other whiles with bitter mockes and mowes
Who mocketh all my paine, & laughs the more I mourn.
That masked Mock-knight was their sport and play.
Amased stands, her selfe so mockt to see
In vaine to mocke, or mockt in vaine to bee:
He laught, and mockt to see him like to swim.
Did mitigate the fiercenesse of their mode,
With equall measure she did moderate
But the milde air with season moderate
To moderate stiffe minds, disposd to striue:
Yet wisely moderated her owne smart,
Him goodly greeted in her modest guise,
With countenance demure, and modest grace,
And in her modest manner thus bespake;
Who rich arayd, and yet in modest guize,
And passe the bonds of modest merimake,
The which them did in modest wise amate,
That was right faire, and modest of demaine,
Vnto the ground she cast her modest eye,
And the strong passion mard her modest grace,
She modest was in all her deedes and words,
Besides her modest countenance he saw
As by his modest semblant, that no euill ment.
Which she did more augment with modest grace,
Yet full of grace and goodly modestee,
She is the fountaine of your modestee;
Doth first peepe forth with bashfull modestee,
Downe to her foot, with carelesse modestee.
With sober gladnesse, and myld modestie,
In word and deede that shew'd great modestie,
Then to the knight with shamefast modestie
And comely courted with meet modestie,
From course of nature and of modestie?
All mindlesse of her wonted modestie,
And next to her sate sober Modestie,
